# Agents Handoff Rule

Applies to any document that passes between agents. These documents are validated against schemas in `cowork/schemas/` and are the interchange format of the agent cell.

## The envelopes

| Schema | Template | Produced by | Consumed by |
|--------|----------|-------------|-------------|
| `program_intake.schema.json` | (inlined in `task_state.intake`) | Intake | Architect |
| `program_spec.schema.json` | `PROGRAM_SPEC_TEMPLATE.md` | Architect | Motion, Integration, Safety, QA |
| `handoff.schema.json` | `HANDOFF_TEMPLATE.md` | Any | Next agent + Orchestrator |
| `review.schema.json` | `QA_REVIEW_TEMPLATE.md` | QA | Orchestrator, Docs |
| `safety_review.schema.json` | `SAFETY_REVIEW_TEMPLATE.md` | Safety | Orchestrator, Docs |
| `dataset_entry.schema.json` | `INGESTION_ENTRY_TEMPLATE.md` | Ingestion pipeline / Research | QA |
| `task_state.schema.json` | `task_state.template.json` | Orchestrator | All |

## Pre-flight

Before acting on an incoming envelope, validate:

1. It conforms to its `schema_in`.
2. All `source:` citations resolve (either to a `fanuc_dataset/` entry by `id`, or to an in-scope `customer_programs/<c>/...` file path with the `canonical: false` acknowledged).
3. `created_at` and `created_by` are populated.
4. Required fields are not empty or placeholder-only.

If any pre-flight check fails, refuse the handoff; log a `conflict` in `task_state.conflicts[]` and kick back to the Orchestrator.

## Body structure

Every handoff document follows:

```
---
<schema-valid frontmatter>
---

# <Title>

## Summary

## Inputs
- Source envelope reference
- Dataset citations

## Findings / Proposal

## Decisions
- Decision + rationale + citation

## Open Questions

## Next Agent
- name:
- input: path to envelope they'll read
- schema_in: which schema they validate against
```

## Citations

Every claim in `Findings / Proposal` has a citation:

- `source: [FANUC_REF_J_Motion]` - dataset entry.
- `source: [customer_programs/ldj_blm/integration_notes/BLM_press_brake.md#modbus-map]` - customer-scoped, flagged as context.
- `source: [external: "FANUC R-30iB V9 Operator's Manual", pages: 412-418, accessed: 2026-04-21]` - external but not yet normalized. Raises a gap ticket.

No citation = no claim. If you cannot cite, mark the point as `speculative: true` and kick to research.

## task_state.json mechanics

- One `task_state.json` per task directory.
- Orchestrator owns writes to top-level fields (`status`, `updated_at`, `conflicts`, `handoffs`, `artifacts`).
- Specialist agents append under their namespaced key (`intake`, `architect`, `motion`, `integration`, `safety`, `qa`, `documentation`).
- Never overwrite another agent's key. If you need to amend, add a revision entry with `supersedes: <prev_revision>`.

## Conflict handling

If two agents disagree:

```json
{
  "conflicts": [
    {
      "id": "conflict-001",
      "raised_by": "safety",
      "about": "architect.motion.speed",
      "position_a": "Architect proposes 1500 mm/s",
      "position_b": "Safety: DCS CSC1 limit is 1000 mm/s",
      "citations": ["FANUC_SAFE_DCS_Cartesian_Speed_Check", "customer_programs/ldj_blm/integration_notes/dcs_config.md"],
      "resolution": null
    }
  ]
}
```

The Orchestrator resolves per `cowork/workflows/*.md`. If canon resolves it, defer. If canon is silent, escalate.

## Close the loop

When a handoff is produced, append to `task_state.handoffs[]`:

```json
{
  "from": "architect",
  "to": "motion-synthesis",
  "envelope": "PROGRAM_SPEC_PNS0001.md",
  "schema": "program_spec.schema.json",
  "at": "2026-04-21T10:15:00Z"
}
```

And update `task_state.status` as appropriate (`in_architect`, `in_motion`, `in_safety`, ...).
